  <p>Initially, <b>D[u]</b> =3D +=E2=88=9E (practically, a large value like=
 10<sup>9</sup>) =E2=88=80<b>u</b> =E2=88=88 <b>V\{s}</b>, but <b>D[s]</b> =
=3D <b>D[0]</b> =3D 0.<br>Initially, <b>p[u]</b> =3D -1 (to say 'no predece=
ssor') =E2=88=80<b>u</b> =E2=88=88 <b>V</b>.</p><br><p>Now click <span clas=
s=3D"slide-actions">Dijkstra(0)</span> =E2=80=94 don't worry about the deta=
ils as they will be explained later =E2=80=94 and wait until it is over (ap=
proximately 10s on this small graph).</p><br><p>At the end of that SSSP alg=
orithm, <b>D[s]</b> =3D <b>D[0]</b> =3D 0 (unchanged) and <b>D[u]</b> =3D <=
b>=CE=B4(s, u)</b> =E2=88=80<b>u</b> =E2=88=88 <b>V</b><br>e.g., <b>D[2]</b=
> =3D 6, <b>D[4]</b> =3D 7 (these values are stored as <span style=3D"color=
: red;">red text</span> under each vertex).<br>At the end of that SSSP algo=
rithm, <b>p[s]</b> =3D <b>p[0]</b> =3D -1 (the source has no predecessor), =
but <b>p[v]</b> =3D the origin of the <span style=3D"color: red;">red edges=
</span> for the rest, e.g., <b>p[2]</b> =3D 0, <b>p[4] =3D 2</b>.</p><br><p=
>Thus, if we are at <b>s</b> =3D 0 and want to go to vertex 4, we will use =
shortest path 0 =E2=86=92 2 =E2=86=92 4 with path weight 7. In the explorat=
ion mode, after any SSSP algorithm has been completed, you can hover on any=
 vertex and notice the shortest path from source vertex <b>s</b> to that ve=
rtex is highlighted.</p>

