;left:50%;margin-left:-250px;width:500px;">
  <p>Every time a vertex is processed, we relax its neighbors. In total, <b=
>E</b> edges are processed.</p><br><p>If by relaxing <b>edge(u, v)</b>, we =
have to decrease <b>D[v]</b>, we call the O(log <b>V</b>) DecreaseKey() ope=
ration in <a href=3D"https://visualgo.net/en/heap"><u>Binary Min Heap</u></=
a> (harder to implement as C++ STL priority_queue/Python heapq/Java Priorit=
yQueue does not support this operation efficiently <i>yet</i>) or simply de=
lete the old entry and then re-insert a new entry in <a href=3D"https://vis=
ualgo.net/en/avl"><u>balanced BST like AVL Tree</u></a> (which also runs in=
 O(log <b>V</b>), but this is much easier to implement, just use C++ STL se=
t/Java TreeSet =E2=80=94 unfortunately not natively supported in Python).</=
p><br><p>Therefore, this part is O(<b>E</b> log <b>V</b>).</p><br><p>Thus i=
n overall, Dijkstra's algorithm runs in O(<b>V</b> log <b>V</b> + <b>E</b> =
log <b>V</b>) =3D O((<b>V</b>+<b>E</b>) log <b>V</b>) time, which is much f=
aster than the O(<b>V=C3=97E</b>) Bellman-Ford algorithm.</p>

